David"Although arriving 10 minutes late to the interview is not the right way to start the interview, overall I thought he is a good candidate.  Below are a few things I picked up during the interview along with my thoughts.

1.	Compensation
1.	His current base salary is $107k with quarterly bonuses totaling approximately $20k
2.	He is looking for $140 - $145 in total comp.
3.	Would consider contracting offered, but is seeking full-time role.
2.	 Travel
1.	His primary reason for looking outside of Oracle is travel which is currently 100%.
2.	He has a small daughter and is seeking more opportunities to be with his family.
3.	His objective is to keep his travel to < 25% measured over the year.
3.	In order of priority his decision criteria for a new job includes:
1.	Decreased travel – he enjoys his current job, so would not consider a move that included similar travel.
2.	Career growth – he is happy coming in as a senior developer / architect, but is interested in growth opportunities:
1.	Within a few years, he would like to be in a role which allowed him to provide technical leadership on multiple projects.  
2.	He enjoys participating in sales opportunities
3.	Compensation – see compensation above.
4.	Family values 
1.	Does not want to be "a number".  
4.	Overall
1.	Assuming you and Shridev were comfortable with his responses he seemed technically competent.
1.	He provided specific work examples when explaining how he would approach problems.
2.	He was comfortable saying when he didn't have a specific experience, but offered his initial thought on how he would approach the problem.  
2.	In his current role, he is typically solo on client engagements.  This supports my impression that he does work instead of talks about work.
3.	I did not explore his content management taxonomy experience, but he does list it on this resume.
4.	When asked about open source
1.	He dislikes Oracle licensing model.
2.	Does not feel companies should rely upon software that does not have a formal support model.
3.	Feels commercially supported open source is a good solution (he referenced Alfresco's model).
5.	 Communications
1.	Although I wouldn’t characterize his communication skills as "impeccable" (per his resume), he spoke clearly, succinctly, and used relevant examples.
2.	He required very little time to contemplate his answers
6.	He was tardy to the interview
1.	He was apologetic both before and after the interview for not allowing enough time to get here from Cumming.
7.	Appearance
1.	He was dressed professionally.

In summary, provided you and Shridev are comfortable with his technical skills and you are comfortable that we can meet his compensation needs, I think we should move forward with him."

Given two Sorted Arrays, devise an algorithm to find the First common element in both arrays.
(5,7,9,12,22,22,50,75)  Any array with numbers will suffice – put on board or paper for him to see
(1,6,8,9,13,22,90)  In the second array, have at least two numbers which match numbers in the first array
